Line 1. Epod. 13. 6 ‘Tu vina Torquato move Consule pressa meo.’ The date implies that Corvinus is promised not merely old wine (it was of the vintage of nc. 65, when L. Manlius Torquatus and L. Aurelius Cotta were coss, and therefore must have been at least 35 years old), but also wine which carried with it personal reminiscences of the poet’s own life, and which therefore it is a proof of friendship to offer. Cp. the dating of the Sabine wine which is offered to Maecenas in 1. 20.

The point of imagining these possible effects of the wine on different tempers seems to lie in the expression of its potency, ⁶ it must have some great effect, whatever that be ’; and the stress is really laid rather on the last of each pair of alternatives ‘ seu . . sive,’ ‘ seu . . seu.’ This is shown by the insertion of ‘pia testa‘ in a place where it is intended to exert its influenee on the whole stanza, and by the repeti- tion, after that ‘quocunque nomine' has again reopened the question of the tendency of the wine, of the commendation ‘ moveri digna bona die.’
